<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911010-0008</DOCNO><DOCID>911010-0008.</DOCID><HL>   Law:   Group of Companies   Settles FTC Charges   On Job Applicants</HL><DATE>10/10/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><CO>   LABOR MD MZ</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)</IN><NS>LABOR, UNIONS, STRIKES, WAGES, RECRUITMENT (LAB)LAW andamp; LEGAL ISSUES AND LEGISLATION (LAW)</NS><GV>FEDERAL TRADE COMMISSION (FTC)</GV><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)GEORGIA (GA)MISSOURI (MO)NEW JERSEY (NJ)NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)PENNSYLVANIA (PA)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- A group of companies, including McDonnellDouglas Corp. and units of R.H. Macy andamp; Co., settled FederalTrade Commission charges of failing to tell rejected jobapplicants they weren't hired partly because of their creditrecords.   The consent agreement involved New York-based Macy'sNortheast Inc., Macy retail outlets in Atlanta and SanFrancisco, and Macy's I. Magnin store in San Francisco;Macy's Data and Credit Services Corp. of Cranford, N.J.;Kobacker Co. of Columbus, Ohio, which sells shoes andaccessories through Picway Shoe Stores; Keystone Carbon Co.,a metal-parts manufacturer based in St. Mary's, Pa.; andMcDonnell Douglas.</LP><TEXT>   Employers are required by the Fair Credit Reporting Act totell job applicants when they are rejected on the basis ofcredit data. Companies also must provide the names andaddresses of firms that provided the information. The lawrequires that individuals have an opportunity to challengeincorrect information that credit reports may contain.   Under the proposed consent agreement, the companies mustcomply with the law when evaluating future job applicants,and keep records showing their compliance. The concerns alsomust identify for the rejected applicants the credit bureausthat provided the information used in evaluating their jobapplications.   The consent agreements will be published in the FederalRegister shortly, the commission said, and will be subject topublic comment for 60 days. The commission then will decidewhether to make them final. A consent order is for settlementpurposes only and doesn't constitute an admission of a lawviolation.</TEXT></DOC>